          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>All four of the following conditions cause atlantoaxial instability. Which one d</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>All four of the following conditions cause atlantoaxial instability. Which one does so through erosion of the transverse ligament by inflammatory pannus?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Down syndrome</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Down syndrome causes instability through connective tissue hypotonia that loosens the transverse ligament, not through inflammatory pannus erosion.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Rheumatoid arthritis</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. In rheumatoid arthritis, inflammatory pannus tissue erodes the transverse ligament of the atlas, leading to atlantoaxial instability and widening of the atlantodental interval beyond 3 mm.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Type II odontoid fracture</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A type II odontoid fracture breaks the dens at its base after high-velocity trauma. The transverse ligament itself may remain intact.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Grisel syndrome</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Grisel syndrome is a non-traumatic atlantoaxial subluxation in children, triggered by head and neck infections such as tonsillitis, not by pannus formation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the four causes of atlantoaxial instability: Down syndrome (connective tissue hypotonia), rheumatoid arthritis (pannus erosion), type II odontoid fracture (trauma), and Grisel syndrome (post-infective subluxation in children)."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Rheumatoid arthritis is the classic inflammatory cause. Pannus erodes the transverse ligament, the single most important stabiliser of the atlantoaxial joint."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
