          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The superficial temporal artery is palpable just anterior to the tragus of the ear. What is the primary clinical significance of this artery in patients over fifty years of age?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>It is the preferred site for arterial blood gas sampling</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Arterial blood gas sampling is typically performed from the radial artery at the wrist, not the superficial temporal artery.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It is the standard biopsy site for giant cell arteritis</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Giant cell arteritis (temporal arteritis) is the most common vasculitis in adults over fifty. Temporal artery biopsy is the gold standard for diagnosis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Its occlusion causes middle meningeal artery haemorrhage</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The middle meningeal artery is a branch of the maxillary artery, not the superficial temporal artery. Its rupture causes extradural haematoma.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It serves as the access site for carotid angiography</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Carotid angiography uses the Seldinger technique via the femoral artery, not the superficial temporal artery.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The superficial temporal artery, palpable anterior to the tragus, is the biopsy site for giant cell arteritis. This is a key clinical correlation for surface anatomy of the head and neck."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "The superficial temporal artery, palpable anterior to the tragus, is the standard biopsy site for giant cell arteritis — the most common vasculitis in adults over fifty."
                }
              ],
